I'm not so sure about that. The classes are the same now because we only track GET and LIST which are the same across all blob store in how they work and how we want to track them.
But once we add writes, we'll have to track different kinds of requests (e.g. for GCS we'll track the last request in a resumable upload while in S3 we'd track the requests for starting and ending the a multi-part upload as well as the PUTs for the individual parts).
If we just have one class and an Enum we're either pretty limited by the resolution on the request type we can express or we'll have some merged Enum that contains the implementation details of the various request types for all the plugins.
I guess we could make the thing a little more generic if we wanted to though? We could have an Enum per plugin for the request types and then do something generic like this:
public class BlobStoreStats <T> {

    private final Map<T, AtomicLong> counts = ConcurrentCollections.newConcurrentMap();

    public void track(T opType) {
        counts.computeIfAbsent(opType, k -> new AtomicLong(0)).incrementAndGet();
    }
}
and then use it like e.g.
  stats.track(S3Op.GET);
How about that?

